Q8: I've spent a lot of time looking at plotted data (my background is economics, long ago).
Q11: It was fascinating to see that I spent about the same amount of time on female and nonbinary applicants, that sort of thing.
Q13: I was more lenient with minority applications. I had to spend a little more time on male applicants, especially white ones, to decide how to rate them.
Q16: I wasn't really thinking about load balancing applicants across demographics as I went, I was just being more generous with minority applications. The overall rating stuff isn't as helpful to me as a result.
Q18: I thought the female ones would be higher, but maybe my impression was skewed by that one woman who built a small catapult. It makes sense there'd be more variation there in retrospect because the circumstances non-male applicants were more varied and often involved more family stuff.

Q8: I didn't find it to be very mentally demanding. The walkthrough of the information made it easy to understand and being able to hover over the dots and see all of the applicant information made it easy to digest and see the trends between race, gender, etc. I think it would've been much more mentally demanding if we were not given any instruction on how to navigate the data.
Q11: I didn't find it particularly useful just because there were other factors at play. I spent much more time reviewing the first applicant because I wasn't sure what was to come with the other applicants and then spent less time on later applicants just because I didn't feel the need to note every little thing anymore as almost everyone was showcasing teamwork and collaborative experiences in one form or another, for example. Also sometimes it was quite obvious whether or not an applicant was competitive or not, so I spent less time determining how to rate them. For example, the lowest rated applicants did not need as much time to digest as others, as it was immediately clear to me that they were not of the same caliber as the others, just based on their performance and lack of qualities or experiences that others had. This had nothing to do with race or gender.
Q13: I am not surprised, for the same reasons I outlined in my answer above. For example, taking much much longer on the first applicant as I was learning how to navigate the page and looking at all of the elements available to me, plus taking notes on everything before I realized it was not so pertinent to, as all applicants had some similarities. I also was not surprised that I spent less time on the lowest rated applicants as it was easier to rate them seeing that they had lower academic performance and lacked other qualities and experiences which I saw as favorable in other applicants.
Q16: I found this to be moderately useful. I rated this as moderately useful because I do not believe I took into account race, gender, etc. I was looking at the applicants based on their merits and how I felt about those. This was reflected quite a bit in my rating distribution. Often as I looked across a line, it alternated, for example: white, black, white, black. so there was no apparent favoring of one over the other. I also ranked this as moderately useful simply because I found it interesting to look at.
Q18: I am not surprised at all, as I consider myself to be accepting of all, regardless of race and gender, and when it comes to things like applicants, I look at it as basing it on whoever's merits indicate that they performed best. For example, the applicant who was valedictorian (ranked first in class) would always be my number 1 pick, regardless of race or gender or any other demographic data.

Q11: They were extremely useful because they allowed me to quickly assess my biases and how much time I spent on each attribute. This allowed me to gain a larger perspective on the situation and address my behavior appropriately.
Q13: Yes I was surprised that I spent so much more time on non-binary people. I had no idea I was doing that! I was also surprised, and perhaps disappointed with myself, for giving white people higher scores and more time than black people. I was not conscious that I was doing this and it is good to know.
Q16: I found them extremely useful as I was able to quickly discern my biases on how I was rating applicants based on attributes. This allowed me to adjust my behavior appropriately to give an even better, more accurate assessment.
Q18: I was a bit surprised and disappointed that I had given black people lower ratings than white people. I was not conscious that I was doing this and thus was surprised.

Q5_6_TEXT: I do keep in touch with a lot of people who do admissions. I've seen a lot of examples of personal essays, in particular.
Q8: It's a lot of data all at once, but it's clearly labeled and interactive, so it's easy to understand.
Q11: I can see how it would be useful to know if you're giving more time to one demographic or another, and adjust accordingly. Mine was a bit skewed by spending a lot of time on my first profile, however, and I can see that kind of issue cropping up for other reasons, as well.
Q13: I wasn't aware I was spending slightly less time on profiles of nonbinary people, but there are also fewer of them, so it could have just been selection bias.
Q16: I always worry about unconscious bias. I could immediately look at my very low or very high ratings and see that, yes, they deserved those ratings.
Q18: Nothing seems unwarranted or unfair to me, which was my goal.

Q8: The instructions were very clearly spelled out, and the visuals were easy to understand and navigate.
Q11: I began reading the letters from applicants. Some were easier to work through than others. Some were more obviously competitive than others. However, there were those who showed they were quite competent in other ways.
Q13: Except for one person, there did not seem to be a big difference. I was surprised because the first thing I looked at was not gender or race. Yet, there was some difference.
Q16: The Overall Rating Distribution helped me consider how fair I was. There were students in both races that did extremely well.
Q18: Although the ratings were not exactly even, if I remember correctly they were close. As a white person, I still wonder what caused me to have the whites a little ahead.
